<DOC><DOCNO> AP900618-0168 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-90 1250EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a BC-APIndustryNews 5thAdd   06-18 0567</FIRST><SECOND>BC-AP Industry News, 5th Add,0588</SECOND><HEAD>Historical Society Begins Computer News Index Project</HEAD><DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Omaha World-Herald is donating $150,000to help start an electronic index of its clip files to be madeavailable to the public.   The Douglas County Historical Society installed eight computerson June 13 for its ``Living Morgue.''   Roger Reeves, curator of the historical society, said the clips,which fill three rooms, will first have to be preserved.   ``When we first got them, they were crunched into smallenvelopes. We'll unfold them and put them into acid-free files todeter any more aging. Those that are too delicate will bephotocopied on acid-free paper.''   During the second phase, Reeves and a staff of five will enterbrief summaries of each story into the computers, which will beaccessible to colleges and public libraries statewide for a fee.  </TEXT><HEAD>Newspaper Closes in Nyssa</HEAD><DATELINE>NYSSA, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Publication of the monthly Nyssa Gate CityJournal has been suspended, general manager Jim Allison said.   Owners Ted and Kay Grossman, now living in Washington's PugetSound area, had tried to sell the paper for about five years,Allison said.   Allison said the paper, with a monthly circulation of 1,500,lost money for several years. The last issue was published May 23.</TEXT><HEAD>Striking Journalists Publish Own Newspaper</HEAD><DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Journalists stood on street corners hawkinga newspaper they published on their own after launching Norway'sfirst newspaper strike in 44 years.   The 32-page tabloid Avisa, the Norwegian word for newspaper,appeared on June 11, a day after wage negotiations collapsed. Itcompeted with regular newspapers that succeeded in publishing thineditions that day.   The Norwegian Union of Journalists had ordered strikes at eightmajor newspapers and the national news service NTB. Norway'spublishers association responded by locking out reporters from 57other newspapers.   In all, about 2,000 journalists were on strike or locked out.   Employers offered less than half the journalists' demand of a4.57 percent increase on their $34,460 average annual salary,reports said.</TEXT><HEAD>Serbian Journalists Complain of Bias in Belgrade TV News</HEAD><DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Independent journalists' groups inSerbia complained of bias in Belgrade TV coverage of ananti-Communist rally and demanded criminal charges be broughtagainst the Communist director.   ``We consider that television reports before, during and afterthe opposition rally ... represent a drastic violation ofjournalistic ethics,'' said a statement released June 15 byBelgrade Television's independent employees union.   More than 30,000 people from the one-party state of Serbia, thelargest of Yugoslavia's six republics, demonstrated in Belgrade onJune 13 demanding free elections and an end to Communist rule intheir state.   The main rally ended peacefully, but police later used clubs todisperse demonstrators who went to the TV station to demandcoverage of their demands and the resignation of Dusan Mitevic, aCommunist official appointed to head the state-run TV last year.   Belgrade TV and Serbia's state-run press have described therally as ``a betrayal of Serbia'' and its participants as ``fascisthooligans.'' They demand a purge of reporters from Belgrade'sindependent radio station, which gave comprehensive coverage to theevent.   A similar protest about coverage was made against the newspaperPolitika, an outlet of Serbia's ruling Communists, by 37 Politikareporters. Its story June 14 on the rally was headlined, ``TheAnti-Serbian Gathering Was Unsuccessful.''</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>